In the early 1960s, the US Department of Defense created ARPANET, the first network to connect computers. This laid the groundwork for the global internet we know today. Initially intended for secure communication, it paved the way for the World Wide Web.

A British engineer named Tim Berners-Lee then revolutionized the internet in 1989. He created HTML, the standard language for websites, and the Hypertext Transfer Protocol (HTTP) to connect servers and browsers.

The popularization of the internet picked up pace with the introduction of the World Wide Web in 1993. As dial-up connections became widespread, the number of internet users grew exponentially.

Fast-forward to the early 2000s, and we were greeted by the dawn of broadband internet, social media, and cloud storage. Since then, the internet has evolved into a multi-billion-dollar industry driving global innovation.

